\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp.{\b  tetraphyllum} : Stems much-branched. Leaves green, mostly in whorls of 4. Inflorescence lax, much-branched. Stamens (1-)3-5. Seeds usually less than 0·5 mm, punctulate.{\i  Sandy or rocky places, usually inland. Throughout the range of the species}.
\par
\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp.{\b  diphyllum} (Cav.) O. Bolòs & Font Quer,{\i  Collect. Bot.} ({\i Barcelona}) {\b 6:} 356 (1962) ({\i P. diphyllum }Cav.,{\i  P. alsinifolium} auct., non (Biv.) DC.): Annual; stems usually simple. Leaves purplish-tinged, at least near the base of the stems, usually paired. Inflorescence few-flowered, condensed. Stamens 1-3. Seeds like those of subsp. ({\b a}). {\i Sandy places, usually coastal. S.W. Europe; Aegean region}.
\par
\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b c}) Subsp.{\b  alsinifolium }(Biv.) Ball, {\i Jour. Linn. Soc. London} ({\i Bot.}) {\b 16:} 370 (1877) ({\i P. alsinifolium} (Biv.) DC.; incl. {\i P. rotundifolium} Rouy): Stems often branched. Leaves green or purplish-tinged, at least some near the middle of the stem in whorls of 4. Inflorescence few-flowered, condensed. Stamens 5. Seeds at least 0·5 mm, smooth.{\i  Sandy places, usually coastal. W. & S. Europe, northwards to N.W. France}.
\par
\par
\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. P. polycarpoides} (Biv.) Zodda, {\i Nuovo Gior. Bot. Ital.} nov. ser., {\b 15: }347 (1908) ({\i P. alsinifolium} auct., non (Biv.) DC.,{\i  P. peploides} DC.; incl.{\i  P. colomense} Porta). Perennial, with woody stock; stems branched. Leaves obovate to suborbicular, fleshy, usually paired, rarely verticillate; stipules small, greyish. Flowers few, in a lax inflorescence. Sepals 1·5-2 mm, obtuse or acute; petals entire, about as long as the sepals; stamens 5. Seeds 0·5 mm or more, tuberculate.{\i  Rocks, usually coastal. W. Mediterranean region.} Bl Ga Hs It Si.
\par
\par
\pard\f0\fs28 Subsp.{\b  herniarioides} (Ball) Maire & Weiller in Maire,{\i  Fl. Afr. Nord}{\b  9:} 73 (1963), from N.W. Africa, has been reported from Sierra de Gádor, west of Almeria. It differs from subsp.{\b  polycarpoides} by the more compact habit with short, little-branched stems, petals 1/2 as long as the sepals and seeds 0·4-0·5 mm with smaller tubercles.
